jason r tibbetts wrote:
&gt; The pattern of writing an abstract TestCase to test an interface&#39;s
&gt; methods and then subclassing it for each implementation of that
&gt; interface is well-established
&lt;snip /&gt;
 &gt; But what&#39;s a good way to handle this when the CUT
&gt; implements multiple interfaces, each of which has an abstract base test?

If a class implements interfaces A, B and C, then I would tend to want 
Contract Tests for each interface. If we use TestCase subclassing to do 
that in JUnit, then that would mean three test case classes:

1. TestXAsA extends ATests
2. TestXAsB extends BTests
3. TestXAsC extends CTests

This might bother some people, but it doesn&#39;t bother me: I don&#39;t need 
one test case class per production code class.

&gt; I want to write something like the following, but I&#39;m looking for better
&gt; ideas:
&gt; 
&gt; public class FooBar implements Foo, Bar { ... }
&gt; 
&gt; public class BarTestBase extends TestCase {
&gt;    protected Bar bar;
&gt; 
&gt;    public void testSomeMethod() { ... }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; // does NOT subclass FooTestBase or BarTestBase
&gt; public class FooBarTest extends TestCase {
&gt;    static class FooSubclassTest extends FooTestBase {
&gt;      protected void setUp() { foo = new FooBar(); }
&gt;    }
&gt; 
&gt;    static class BarSubclassTest extends BarTestBase {
&gt;      protected void setUp() { foo = new FooBar(); }
&gt;    }
&gt; 
&gt;    public static Test suite() {
&gt;       TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(FooBarTest.class);
&gt;       suite.addTest(new TestSuite(FooSubclassTest.class);  // ?
&gt;       suite.addTest(new TestSuite(BarSubclassTest.class);  // ?
&gt;       return suite;
&gt;    }
&gt; }

You&#39;ve done here what I would do, except you&#39;ve added a suite() method 
to collect all the &quot;FooBar&quot; tests together. Since I usually try to run 
all my tests all the time, I&#39;d get that free.

&gt; Considerations:
&gt; * This keeps all of the tests for the FooBar class in a single file.

I don&#39;t find this important, but that&#39;s personal taste.

&gt; * Because the static inner test classes&#39; names end with &#39;Test&#39;, they&#39;ll
&gt; be picked up automatically by an Ant &lt;junit&gt; task that executes anything
&gt; called &#39;*Test.class&#39;, right? If so, then adding them to the FooBarTest&#39;s
&gt; suite is redundant.

That&#39;s handy.

&gt; * If the inner classes&#39; names end in &#39;Test&#39;, they must be declared
&gt; static in order to prevent a reflection exception when the JUnit test
&gt; loader attempts to invoke them, since they&#39;d have to be instantiated
&gt; within an instance of FooBarTest.

That makes sense.

I think you&#39;re on the right track here. Let us know how it works for 
you. This is one of those deeper examples that no-one has written about 
in detail yet. (Even _JUnit Recipes_ only mentions it in passing.) You 
should write about your experiences with this pattern and share it with 
the world. :)
